docs.abstract: President Trump will give Canada, Mexico and the European Union another 30-day reprieve from steel and aluminum tariffs, delaying punishing levies on key allies.
docs.snippet: President Trump will give Canada, Mexico and the European Union another 30-day reprieve from steel and aluminum tariffs, delaying punishing levies on key allies.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration said on Monday that it would delay a decision to impose steel and aluminum tariffs on the European Union, Canada and Mexico for another 30 days, giving key allies a reprieve as the White House tries to extract concessions from trading partners who have resisted those demands.

headline.main: White House Delays Tariffs on E.U., Canada and Mexico for 30 Days
headline.print_headline: U.S. Delaying Start of Tariffs For Key Allies

docs.abstract: Although the industry has evaded tighter gun control laws, several manufacturers are struggling with bankruptcy and falling sales.
docs.snippet: Although the industry has evaded tighter gun control laws, several manufacturers are struggling with bankruptcy and falling sales.
docs.lead_paragraph: As the school shooting in Parkland, Fla., stokes the national debate over firearms, it may be easy to overlook another major development in the gun world this week.

headline.main: Gun Makers Are Reeling Even as Threat of Regulation Recedes
headline.print_headline: Why Having a Friend in the White House May Be Bad for the Gun Business

byline.original: By Michael Corkery and Tiffany Hsu

docs.abstract: The retailer, which left Taiwan and other territory off the map, said it “respects China’s sovereignty and territorial integrity.” It was the latest mea culpa from a firm careful not to anger Beijing.
docs.snippet: The retailer, which left Taiwan and other territory off the map, said it “respects China’s sovereignty and territorial integrity.” It was the latest mea culpa from a firm careful not to anger Beijing.
docs.lead_paragraph: A Gap T-shirt showing a map of China that omitted territory the country claims as its own has prompted a strong apology from the retailer, the latest in a string of mea culpas from businesses wary of offending the Chinese government.

headline.main: Gap, Wary of Crossing China, Apologizes for T-Shirt’s Map

docs.abstract: A decision by a California judge could force Starbucks and other coffee companies to warn about acrylamide, a chemical that has been linked to cancer.
docs.snippet: A decision by a California judge could force Starbucks and other coffee companies to warn about acrylamide, a chemical that has been linked to cancer.
docs.lead_paragraph: Coffee sellers are mulling how to fight a California judge’s ruling that would require the beverage to be branded with cancer warning labels.

headline.main: Coffee Drinkers Need Cancer Warning, Judge Rules, Giving Sellers the Jitters
headline.print_headline: Judge’s Ruling on Cancer Warning for Coffee Gives Sellers the Jitters

docs.abstract: After Georgia lawmakers punished Delta for removing a discount for N.R.A. members, its chief wrote to employees stressing neutrality on gun control.
docs.snippet: After Georgia lawmakers punished Delta for removing a discount for N.R.A. members, its chief wrote to employees stressing neutrality on gun control.
docs.lead_paragraph: Delta Air Lines said Friday it might scrap promotional offers for all politically contentious organizations after its removal of a discount for National Rifle Association members drew a swift retaliation from Georgia lawmakers.

headline.main: ‘Our Values Are Not for Sale,’ Says Delta C.E.O. as Airline Considers Ending Divisive Discounts
headline.print_headline: Wary of Political Baggage, Delta Rethinks Discounts

docs.abstract: Laurent Potdevin, who joined the yoga pants maker in 2014, stepped down because of behavior that fell short of its standards of conduct, the company said.
docs.snippet: Laurent Potdevin, who joined the yoga pants maker in 2014, stepped down because of behavior that fell short of its standards of conduct, the company said.
docs.lead_paragraph: Laurent Potdevin, the chief executive of Lululemon Athletica, the company famous for its leggings and role in the creation of the athleisure trend, resigned because of behavior that fell short of the athletic apparel maker’s standards of conduct, the company said on Monday.

headline.main: Lululemon’s Chief Executive Resigns Over Behavior

docs.abstract: The coffee chain closed its U.S. stores for several hours to improve its image after the arrests of two black men at a store in Philadelphia brought heavy criticism.
docs.snippet: The coffee chain closed its U.S. stores for several hours to improve its image after the arrests of two black men at a store in Philadelphia brought heavy criticism.
docs.lead_paragraph: For Starbucks, the scope of companywide anti-bias training on Tuesday was easy to measure. Roughly 175,000 employees at 8,000 locations pored over nearly 23,000 iPads, learning about the processing power of unconscious brains and the roots of unconscious bias.

headline.main: Starbucks’s Tall Order: Tackle Systemic Racism in 4 Hours
headline.print_headline: Closing Up Shop For an Afternoon To Address Bias

byline.original: By Rachel Abrams, Tiffany Hsu and John Eligon

docs.abstract: The retail giant is accelerating its efforts in the online-grocery sector as rivals, led by Amazon, wage their own aggressive campaigns for control of America’s kitchen cupboards.
docs.snippet: The retail giant is accelerating its efforts in the online-grocery sector as rivals, led by Amazon, wage their own aggressive campaigns for control of America’s kitchen cupboards.
docs.lead_paragraph: The path to fast and affordable online grocery service is littered with obstacles: refrigeration challenges, storage woes and high transportation costs, among others. But the country’s largest retailers are convinced that it will lead to a lucrative and largely untapped market.

headline.main: Walmart Expands Online Grocery Delivery to 100 Cities
headline.print_headline: Knock Knock, Walmart’s at the Door

byline.original: By Tiffany Hsu and Nick Wingfield

docs.abstract: Seeking a site where users “do not feel threatened,” Bumble will ban images of firearms from its nearly 30 million users.
docs.snippet: Seeking a site where users “do not feel threatened,” Bumble will ban images of firearms from its nearly 30 million users.
docs.lead_paragraph: A few swipes into the popular dating app Bumble, and the diversity of interests is obvious: Users post photos of themselves swinging from trapezes, playing French horns, posing with freshly caught fish and, occasionally, brandishing a handgun or aiming a semiautomatic rifle.

headline.main: Bumble Dating App Bans Gun Images After Mass Shootings
headline.print_headline: Bumble Dating App Bans Gun Photos After Massacre

docs.abstract: Wendell Jamieson, who had led The New York Times’s metro section for five years, issued an apology before leaving the paper. But the reason for his departure was not disclosed.
docs.snippet: Wendell Jamieson, who had led The New York Times’s metro section for five years, issued an apology before leaving the paper. But the reason for his departure was not disclosed.
docs.lead_paragraph: The New York Times announced on Monday that Wendell Jamieson, the newspaper’s metro editor, had resigned after an internal investigation but did not specify the reason for his departure.

headline.main: New York Times Metro Editor Resigns, Citing ‘Mistakes’
headline.print_headline: Times Metro Editor Resigns, Apologizing for ‘Mistakes’
